title: Neutron elastic and inelastic cross section measurements on silicon from 0.8-8 MeV

x4freetext: Neutron elastic and inelastic cross section
measurements on silicon from 0.8-8 MeV

x4freetext: The University of Kentucky Accelerator
Laboratory (UKAL) features a 7 MV single-ended model
CN Van de Graaff accelerator with a terminal-based
bunching system.
The MAIN neutron detector used to
register scattered neutrons was a C6D6 liquid
scintillation detector. The emitted gamma-rays were
recorded with an HPGe detector actively shielded with
a BGO annular detector for Compton suppression.
Cylindrical scattering samples were suspended about 8
cm away from the center of the gas cell at 0.relative
to the direction of the incident beam. The primary
scattering sample was a 7.3 g of high-purity natural
silicon with dimensions 1.58 cm x 1.57 cm (diameter x
height). The efficiency of the MAIN detector was
measured from the neutron angular distribution of the
source reaction in the gas cell. The efficiency was
determined by taking the ratio of the neutron counts,
normalized by the neutron fluence, and the known
source reaction cross sections.
Neutron elastic and inelastic scattering
differential cross sections were measured at angles
between 30 and 155 degrees with incident neutron
energies between 0.8 and 8 MeV. Deexcitation gamma
rays produced in the inelastic scattering process
were also studied for neutron energies between 1.9
and 4.5 MeV. On-pulse neutrons were identified by
time-of-flight (TOF) and pulse-shape discrimination
(PSD) techniques.
Approved by A.P.D.Ramirez on November 1, 2024.

x4freetext: A polyethylene solid cylinder with dimensions 0.96 cm
x 1.49 cm (diameter x height) was used to measure the
1H(n,n)1H cross sections for the absolute
normalization of our (n,n`) data. Additionally,
enriched 56Fe (99.87% 56Fe) and natTi cylindrical
scattering samples with dimensions 1.52 cm x 1.45 cm
and 2.23 cm x 2.55 cm (diameter x height),
respectively, were employed for absolute
normalization of our neutron scattering cross
sections deduced from our gamma-ray production cross
sections.
Cross sections within the quoted total
uncertainties.
The relative uncertainty of the neutron
detector efficiency.
The (n,n`) measurements must be corrected for
attenuation and multiple scattering of the incident
and exiting neutrons. Attenuation depends on the
total cross section at each energy, while multiple
scattering depends strongly upon the elastic
differential cross section. The MULCAT code handles
the combined effect including the experimental
geometry.

were determined from the uncertainties of the a0 fit
parameter, while the uncertainties in the incident
neutron energies were calculated from the width of
the beam pulse and the energy spread due to the gas
target assembly.
